    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1911-12-11T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1911-12-11T00:00:00-05:00" n="147"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d147">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 893.51/695b.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">British Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1911-12-11">
                            <hi rend="italic">December 11, 1911</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Ambassador</hi>: Certain general views of the
                    Government of the United States upon the subject of loans to China in the
                    present juncture were set forth in an aide-mémoire handed the German Ambassador
                    on the 7th instant, and I have the honor now to inclose herewith a copy of that
                        aide-mémoire.<note n="1" xml:id="d147fn1">See <ref target="#pg_103">p.
                            103</ref>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Department of State would not, however, in the light of later reports from
                    Peking, be inclined to oppose its nationals joining with others in the small
                    loan referred to in your excellency’s aide-mémoire of the 8th instant, upon the
                    conditions laid down by the British Minister at Peking, more especially so if
                    the views of the United States as to the broadly international character of such
                    loans should meet with the approval of the other Governments concerned.</p>
                <p>I am [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
